title: For Sale:  Vintage Smith & Wesson Model 19-4 357 Magnum
postcontent: The .357 Magnum is the oldest "magnum" handgun cartridge. Smith & Wesson played a major part in the development and success of the cartridge and revolver that went with it. Firearms writer and experimenter Philip Sharpe is credited for its development during the 1930s when police agencies were asking for a more powerful round. S&W's Dan Wesson agreed to produce a new revolver that would handle "high-intensity" .38 Special loads, but only if Winchester would develop a new cartridge. Winchester introduced the .357 Magnum, which was dimensionally identical to the .38 Special except for a .125 inch longer case, and the first revolvers (referred to as ".357 Magnum Models") were completed by S&W on April 8, 1935. Retired Assistant Chief Patrol Inspector of the U.S. Border Patrol, famous gun fighter, and noted firearms and shooting skills writer Bill Jordan consulted with Smith & Wesson on the design and characteristics of the Model 19. Jordan's idea for a "peace officer's dream"[1] sidearm was a heavy-barreled four-inch K-Frame .357 Magnum with a shrouded barrel like the big N-frame .357 and adjustable sights. After a year of experimentation with improved-strength steels and special heat-treat processes, the result was the .357 Combat Magnum ..

title: For Sale/Trade:  86+ year old Spanish Ruby 7.65 For Sale or Trade
postcontent:
This lovely old pistol is of Spanish origin and modeled after the Browning M1903.  It's chambered in 7.65mm Browning but should also work with .32ACP.  I have not test fired it and do not plan to since it hasn't been inspected by a gunsmith.

The proofmarks found on this pistol are shown in the pictures below.  The shield with a diagonal cross and a crown on top means that the gun was inspected by the proofhouse in Eibar, Spain.  Following that is the initials P.V., which mean that the gun was intended for smokeless powder.  To the right of that, very faded, is a rampaging lion.  This series of 3 marks was used by the Eibar proofhouse between 1923 and 1927.  Before 1923, there were no government marks on Spanish firearms.  Starting in late 1927, they began using a code to indicate the year of construction.  Therefore, this gun is between 86 and 90 years old.  The rampaging lion mark appears on the slide and is visible on the barrel as well.  Under the trigger guard there is a maker's mark of "G.A." and there is a very faint mark on the slide which appears to be another "G.A.".  From the literature I've seen, there is no record of a company using this mark, but there is mention of a man named Gaspar Arizaga who made these pistols, but I don't know if anyone will ever know for sure.

Mechanically, it seems sound.  The magazine seems to be in good condition as well.  I think it has a lot of charm and it'll be a very nice addition to a collection.  

****UPDATE**** - This pistol is old but isn't old enough to ship as a collectible and if you want it shipped I can only send it to an FFL.  Don't email me to ask otherwise.

title: For Sale:  Mossberg MMR
postcontent: This rifle features black phosphate/anodized aluminum finishes, a Stark SE-1 pistol grip with battery compartment, a 6 position adjustable stock by UTI, a Picatinny quad-rail forearm and top rail, rail mounted front/rear adjustable sights, and a stock sling mount. The free float rails are designed to fit all the tactical gear that you can carry. Unlike many ARs, this is a standard feature which you won't end up spending more to upgrade the rail set-ups. It has an efficient autoloading direct-impingement gas system for ejection of spent cartridges and auto reloading. No forward assist is necessary for a rifle this smooth. It does have a dust cover, a large trigger hole, and nice charging handle. The blued barrel is 16.25", rifled for 1 in 9" and ends with the muzzle-flash suppressor. The receiver, magazine release, and charging handle are all well designed to make use and maintenance reliable and easy. The upper and lower separate easily with two pins for service and cleaning. The receiver accepts 5.56 Nato ammunition as well as .223 Remington brass or steel casings. It has a 31 round capacity and is a real front-runner in the AR style market. Colt also makes a good quad rail set-up like this, but is generally much more costly. Mossberg redefined affordable with .223s and the .22lr. They have been around over 90 years. They must be doing something right. Mossberg offers their one year manu. warranty on this product. I have additional 30 round factory Mossberg magazines for sale.
